'''Bill Cullen''' (born 20 May 1942) is an [[Ireland|Irish]] businessman and [[philanthropist]]. He is the former owner of the [[Renault|Renault Ireland]] franchise<ref name="bbc">[http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/desertislanddiscs_20031019.shtml Biography at BBC.co.uk]</ref> until it was taken under more direct control by Renault in 2007. A relatively well-known figure in Ireland, Cullen has made numerous appearances on [[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>'s]] ''[[The Late Late Show]]'' and his autobiography became a best-seller.<ref name="tv3">[http://www.tv3.ie/shows.php?request=theapprentice TV3's ''The Apprentice'' microsite]</ref> He is listed as one of Ireland<U+2019>s top 100 businessmen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intertradeireland.com/bill-cullen.cfm|title='Bill Cullen'|accessdate=2009-09-27|publisher=''[[InterTradeIreland]]''}}</ref>

==Biography==

===Early life===
Born into poverty in the Summerhill area of [[Northside Dublin]] during [[The Emergency (Ireland)|The Emergency]], Bill Cullen was the eldest of fourteen children, seven boys and seven girls. Cullen was born in a [[caul]] which was considered a good luck omen at the time.  His mother, Mary Darcy was a fruit seller and Cullen started trading at market stalls from a very young age.<ref name="tv3"/><ref name="bbc"/> His father Billy Cullen, her husband was for the most part unemployed, working on the docks and earning a laborers wage. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishconnectionsmag.com/archives/v3i4/cullen.htm |title='Bill Cullen'|accessdate=2009-09-27|publisher=''[[Irish Connections]]''}} </ref>

===Career===
He finished his education with the [[Christian Brothers]] at the age of thirteen to work on the markets full-time, selling fruit, vegetables and whatever else he could as a means of supporting his family.  In 1956 Bill got a job as a messenger boy at Waldens [[Ford]] Dealer and worked his way up through the company to be appointed director general of  Waldens in 1965.  He went on to set up the Fairlane Motor Company in [[Tallaght]] in 1977 which he developed into the biggest Ford dealership in Ireland by 1981. In 1986 he took over the franchise from for Renault car distribution  from [[Waterford Crystal]]. The initial purchase price of the operation was only a <U+00A3>1 however the deal entailed taking on a debt burden of <U+00A3>18 million. <ref name="Irish Independent"></ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://esoc.ucc.ie/Speaker%20Profiles/billCullen.htm|title='Speaker Profiles...Bill Cullen'|accessdate=2009-09-27|publisher=''ESOC, University College Cork Entrepreneurship Society''}}</ref> This company became known as the  Glencullen Group and the Renault distribution arm became known as Glencullen Distributors.  Turnover of the business grew to <U+20AC>350 Million at its peak.   <ref>{{cite book | last = Cullen | first = Bill | title = It's a Long Way from Penny Apples | publisher = Forge Books | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-0765307101}}</ref> In April 2006 Bill was awarded the distinction of Chevalier de la [[L<U+00E9>gion d'honneur]] by decree of the President of the French Republic for his leadership in the turnaround of Renault Ireland from near bankruptcy. In November 2007, the Renault operation was taken over by Renault S.A.S after achieving sales of 11,900 in 2006.  It now operates as a subsidiary of the parent company. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corkindependent.com/motoring/motoring/renault-acquires-irish-importer/|author=Michael Moroney|title='Renault acquires Irish importer'|publisher='[[Cork Independent]]'|date=2007-10-11|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>  He continues to own Ireland's largest Renault retailer, CityGate Motor Group. It has six dealerships around the country - three of which are in Dublin. <ref name="Irish Independent">{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/penny-apple-tycoon-will-get-millions-925644.html|author=Joe Brennan|title='Penny Apple tycoon will get millions'|work=[[Irish Independent]]|date=2007-07-03|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>  He also set up and owns the Europa Academy, a training facility in [[Swords, Dublin|Swords]], north County Dublin. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europaacademy.com/article.aspx?idarticle=6&idcategory=2|title='BILL CULLEN Takes on Academic Establishment'|title='Europa Academy'|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>  He took over the the Muckross Park Hotel in [[Killarney]] in 1990 with his partner, Jackie Lavin, Who is also his business partner.  The hotel achieved 5 Star status in 2007.  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arts-sport-tourism.gov.ie/publications/release.asp?ID=1989|title='Speech by John O'Donoghue,Minister for Arts, Sport and Tourism at Muckross Park Hotel 5 Star Award'|publisher='Dept. Arts, Sport and Tourism'|date=2007-05-14|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

===Other business positions===
As well as his interests in the motor and hotel industries, Cullen also hold executive positions in other areas:-

* In March 2009 Cullen  became an [[Executive Editor]] of ''RSVP'' business magazine <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fuzion.ie/index.cfm?page=viewNews&newsId=233|title='BILL CULLEN JOINS RSVP BUSINESS AS EXECUTIVE EDITOR'|publisher='Fuzion Communications'|date=2009-03-27|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

* Bill Cullen sits on the board of Directors of [[Dublin Airport Authority]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dublinairportauthority.com/company-profile/board-of-directors.html|title='DAA Board of Directors|publisher='[[Dublin Airport Authority]]'|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

* Cullen also offers his services as a [[motivational speaker]] to Schools college and the business community. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speakersolutions.ie/Bill_Cullen/Default.418.html|title='Bill Cullen'|publisher='Speaker Solutions'|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

===Homes===
He owns a 43-room mansion in [[County Kildare]] and residences in [[Florida]] and [[County Kerry]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rteguide.ie/2008/0922/star.html|title='Bill Cullen The Apprentice'|publisher='[[RTE Guide]]'|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

==Philanthropological work ==
Cullen set up and is a director of the charity "The Irish Youth Foundation" which raises <U+20AC>1.5 million a year for youth projects in Ireland. All royalties from Cullen's 2002 autobiography, ''It's a Long Way from Penny Apples'', were donated to this charity.<ref name="post">[http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2002/01/20/story609267728.asp The ''Sunday Business Post'' - Review of "It's A Long Way From Penny Apples" - Sunday, January 20, 2002]</ref>
 
Cullen set up the Bill Cullen Sunshine Scholarships Fund in 2001 in order to assist young athletes make the transition to senior athletics while continuing their third level education in Ireland. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.dcu.ie/news/press/2004/p0904a.shtml|title='<U+20AC>200,000 Corporate investment into Irish athletics announced'||publisher='[[Dublin City University]]'|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

In February 2005, Bill Cullen brokered a sponsorship deal for [[Home Farm F.C.]], a club which he used to play for, worth  <U+20AC>1,000,000 in a sponsorship deal with several groups with support from [[Renault|Renault Ireland]]  The aim was to establish the club as a major soccer academy.  
The Irish Department of Sports, Arts and Tourism, the Irish Youth Foundation and the club president, [[Tony O'Reilly]] also contributed to the fund.  As part of the arrangement Home Farm jerseys featured the Renault logo alongside the club's distinctive crest. 
<ref>{{cite web|author=Trailer park|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/home-farm-in-pound1m-sponsorship-deal-275235.html |title=www.independent.ie |work=[[Irish Independent]]|date=2005-02-22 |accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eleven-a-side.com/offthefield/irish_soccer_detail.asp?newsid=16134&l=1 |title=Home Farm unveil Renault deal|publisher=eleven-a-side.com |date=2005-02-22 |accessdate=2009-06-23}}</ref>

===Recognition of achievements===
In 1998, he  was a recipient of the Lord Mayor's Award for his work with the disadvantaged young people of Dublin. 

In September 2004, he was awarded the inaugural Princess Grace Humanitarian Award. 

Bill was named Maxol Irish Motor Industry Person of the Year 2000.  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://irishcar.com/00novnews.htm|title=Bill Cullen is Maxol Irish Motor Industry Person|publisher=Irishcar.com|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>
 
He was conferred with an honorary Doctorate of Law of Maynooth University in May 2005 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://communications.nuim.ie/press/170505.shtml|title='AUTHOR AND BUSINESSMAN BILL CULLEN RECEIVES HONORARY DOCTORATE at NUI MAYNOOTH'|publisher=[[NUI Maynooth]]|date=2005-05-17|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

==Involvement in the Media==
Cullen is a popular figure in the irish media and is considered a minor celebrity, appearing on television shows, such as ''[[The Late Late Show]]'', ''[[Tubridy Tonight]]'' and ''[[The Restaurant]]'' on RTE <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/tv/therestaurant/cullen/cullen_bill.html|title='The Restaurant'|publisher=[[RTE.ie]]|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/tv/tubridytonight/20060304.html|title='Tubridy Tonight'|publisher='[[RTE.ie]]'|accessdate=2009-09-27}} </ref>
He has been parodied by [[Tom Dunne]] for several years on the [[Today FM]] ''[[Gift Grub]]'' comedy segment.  This has led to him being affectionately known as "Dr. Bill because of his honorary doctorate.  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribune.ie/news/article/2008/sep/21/profile-bill-cullen-jackie-lavin-whos-the-real-bos/|title='Profile: Bill Cullen & Jackie Lavin - Who's the real boss?'|work=[[Sunday Tribune]]|date=2008-09-21|accessdate=2009-09-27}} </ref> Most recently he has taken on the role as key business "guru" in the Irish version of TV show ''[[The Apprentice (Irish TV series)|The Apprentice]]''.<ref name="tv3"/>

===The Apprentice===
{{main|The Apprentice (Irish TV series)}}

In June 2008, [[TV3 Ireland|TV3]] began inviting applications for an Irish version of popular television [[media franchise|franchise]] ''[[The Apprentice (TV series)|The Apprentice]]''. In the programme, Cullen takes on the role filled in the [[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|U.S. version]] by [[Donald Trump]], and in the [[The Apprentice (UK TV series)|UK version]] by [[Alan Sugar]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/cullen-to-be--the-irish--sir-alan-1401904.html|author='Nick Webb'|title='Cullen to be the Irish Sir Alan'|work=[[Irish Independent]]|date=2008-06-09|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref> His partner Jackie Lavin also acts as a mentor to the apprentices. The show started its second season in September 2009.

==Books==
<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Penny apples 2.jpg|thumb|Bill Cullens autobiography. Royalties from this book were donated to the Irish Youth Foundation |{{deletable image-caption|1=Monday, 5 October 2009}}]] -->
Cullen released his autobiography entitled ''It's a Long Way from Penny Apples'' (ISBN 9780765310439) in 2002 detailing his life growing up in inner city Dublin and rising to become one or Irelands most succesful business people.  

In 2006 Cullen released his  second book ''Golden Apples: Six Simple Steps to Success'' (ISBN 03408389810, a self help book in which he details principles to achieving business success.

==Politics==
Cullen is not affiliated to any political party however, Glencullen Holdings made political donations during 2002 of <U+20AC>13,459. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribune.ie/article/2003/jul/27/car-magnate-cullens-15m-dividend-a-long-way-from-p/?q=bill%20cullen|author='BRIAN CAREY'|title='Car magnate Cullen's .1.5m dividend a long way from penny apples'|work=[[Sunday Tribune]]|date=2003-07-27|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

Cullen has been fiercely critical of the the [[Irish Green Party|Green Party]] since it came to power, particularly the effect the change in [[Vehicle Registration Tax]] and motor taxation policy in July 2008 has had on the Irish motor industry, blaming them for the collapse in new vehicle sales in 2009, saying that these changes were unnecessary. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.munster-express.ie/business/bill-cullen-green-party-is-killing-the-motor-trade|author=Dermot Keyes|title= 'Bill Cullen:Green Party is killing the motor trade'|work=[[Munster Express]]|date=2009-06-05|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.ie/en/news/latest_news/bill_cullen_s_unfair_attack_cannot_go_unchallenged_boyle|author='[[Dan Boyle]]'|title='Bill Cullen's unfair attack cannot go unchallenged'|publisher='[[Irish Green Party|Green Party]]'|date=2009-05-11|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

Cullen is one of a number of high profile members along with [[Packie Bonner]] and [[Mick Galwey]] of the group 'We Belong' who are campaigning for a yes vote in the second Irish constitutional referendum on the [[Lisbon Treaty]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0727/eulisbon.html|title='IBEC: Lisbon rejection was damaging'|publisher=RTE.ie|date=2008-07-27|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

==Trivia==
Bill Cullen took the [[Guinness World Record]] for the largest ever book signing in Easons, [[O<U+2019>Connell Street]] on 16th April 2005 by signing 1849 copies of Golden Apples in 10.5 hours. This was 32 copies more then the previous record. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenapples.ie/goldenapples/worldrecord.htm|title='A GOLDEN MOMENT FOR BILL CULLEN'|publisher='Goldenapples.ie|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>
<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncirl.ie/inside.asp?pageId=2255&sectionId=49&level=2|title='Bill Cullen'|publisher='[[National College of Ireland]]'|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

Bill Cullen is booked to be one of the first passengers to take a flight into space on [[Richard Branson]]s [[Virgin Galactic]] service at a cost of $200,000. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.astronomy.ie/virgingalactic.html|author=Yavanna Evans|title='5 Irish People to Become Astronauts '|publisher='[[Astronomy Ireland]]'|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>

